The proposed models consistently outperform natural baselines on both datasets, with the best baseline being Slate-wise Transformer. In particular,
on ContentWise the best model is AdvNCM with RANCM close behind in terms of <math alttext="\mathrm{F}_{1}" class="ltx_Math" display="inline" id="S4.p1.4.m4.1">
  <semantics id="S4.p1.4.m4.1a">
    <msub id="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1" xref="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.cmml">
      <mi id="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.2" mathvariant="normal" xref="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.2.cmml">F</mi>
      <mn id="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.3" xref="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.3.cmml">1</mn>
    </msub>
    <annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content" id="S4.p1.4.m4.1b">
      <apply id="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.cmml" xref="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1">
        <csymbol cd="ambiguous" id="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.1.cmml" xref="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1">subscript</csymbol>
        <ci id="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.2.cmml" xref="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.2">F</ci>
        <cn id="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.3.cmml" type="integer" xref="S4.p1.4.m4.1.1.3">1</cn>
      </apply>
    </annotation-xml>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex" id="S4.p1.4.m4.1c">\mathrm{F}_{1}</annotation>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-llamapun" id="S4.p1.4.m4.1d">roman_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math>,
but on RL4RS the situation is different, with SCOT being best. This is possibly due to the high fraction of positive interactions in RL4RS; this is definitely the reason for low RANCM performance: on RL4RS it usually halts far too early.
Second, on average trainable embeddings improve the results.
Third, there is a significant gap between GRU baselines and NCM which is based on the same architecture; this confirms our hypothesis that readout is an important improvement.

but on RL4RS the situation is different, with SCOT being best. This is possibly due to the high fraction of positive interactions in RL4RS; this is definitely the reason for low RANCM performance: on RL4RS it usually halts far too early.
Second, on average trainable embeddings improve the results.
Third, there is a significant gap between GRU baselines and NCM which is based on the same architecture; this confirms our hypothesis that readout is an important improvement.

but on RL4RS the situation is different, with SCOT being best. This is possibly due to the high fraction of positive interactions in RL4RS; this is definitely the reason for low RANCM performance: on RL4RS it usually halts far too early.
Second, on average trainable embeddings improve the results.
Third, there is a significant gap between GRU baselines and NCM which is based on the same architecture; this confirms our hypothesis that readout is an important improvement.
